        <section class="intro-section mb-12">
            <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
            <p>
                <strong>Web Intents</strong> are the architectural configuration used by components to decouple their <em>functional logic</em> from a specific <em>User Experience (UX)</em>.
            </p>
            <p>
                By defining the "intent" of an interaction (e.g. "Selection", "Navigation", "Feedback") rather than its implementation, we allow a single component to be reused across vastly different Design Systems (Material, Fluent, Carbon) and form factors without code changes.
            </p>
            <p>
                This enables the "Write Once, Run Everywhere" promise for UI components: the same <code>&lt;List&gt;</code> component can verify as a dense, mouse-driven data grid on Desktop and a spacious, touch-driven collection on Mobile, purely by swapping the active Intent Provider.
            </p>
            <p>
                Crucially, this system pairs with <strong><a href="/projects/webtraits/">Web Traits</a></strong> to ensure zero overhead.
                Since the component only declares <em>intent</em>, the actual code implementation (e.g., the complex physics engine for "Swipe to Archive") is only loaded if that specific intent is active, keeping bundles lean.
            </p>

            <h3 id="philosophy">Philosophy</h3>
            <p>
                Each intent documents the <strong>complete vocabulary</strong> of UX possibilities for a given concern — not a single prescribed solution.
                For example, the Loader Intent doesn't say "use a spinner"; it catalogs every way loading states can affect the user experience
                (blocking strategies, progress indication, timing, skeleton vs. spinner, initial load vs. transition)
                so that an application can <strong>declare</strong> its chosen profile.
            </p>
            <p>
                This research-backed vocabulary is informed by design system analysis (Material, Carbon, Fluent, Spectrum, Apple HIG) and
                UX research (Nielsen Norman Group, perceived performance studies). Intents may recommend approaches based on evidence,
                but they never enforce a single way. The application decides.
            </p>

            <h3 id="intents-vs-blocks">Intents vs. Blocks</h3>
            <p>
                Intents define <em>what</em> the user should experience (the UX contract).
                <a href="/projects/webblocks/">Blocks</a> define <em>how</em> it's implemented (the technical contract).
                A Loader Intent declares "use soft-blocking with debounced timing";
                the implementing Block decides whether to use <code>aria-busy</code>, a <code>&lt;progress&gt;</code> element,
                or a CSS shimmer animation to fulfill that intent.
            </p>
            <p>
                This separation means an application can swap its entire loading UX — from spinners to skeletons —
                by changing intent configuration, without modifying component source code or even recompiling.
                The trait system loads only the rendering code needed for the active intent profile.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section id="proposed-intents" class="section-card">
            <h3 id="proposed-standard-intents">Proposed Intents</h3>
            
            <div class="standards-grid">
                {% for intent in intents %}
                <a href="/intents/{{ intent.id }}/" class="standard-card">
                    <div class="flex justify-between items-start mb-3">
                        <h4 id="intent-{{ intent.id }}" class="text-lg font-bold m-0 text-gray-900">{{ intent.name }}</h4>
                    </div>
                    <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-4">{{ intent.summary }}</p>
                    <div style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
                        {{ projectStatus(intent.status) }}
                    </div>
                </a>
                {% endfor %}
            </div>
        </section>

         <section id="implementation" class="section-card">
            <h3 id="implementation-details">How It Works</h3>
            <p>
                Intents can be applied in two ways, depending on your architecture:
            </p>
            <ul class="mb-4 list-disc pl-5">
                <li><strong>Runtime Contexts</strong>: For dynamic preferences (e.g., user toggles settings). implementations are loaded and swapped on the fly.</li>
                <li><strong>Build-Time Selection</strong>: For fixed application profiles. This allows for dead-code elimination (e.g. if "Compact" is selected, "Comfortable" code is never bundled).</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="mb-4">
                Both strategies rely on the same <a href="/projects/webinjectors/">Web Injectors</a> syntax. 
                In a dynamic environment, the resolution happens at runtime. If a compiler is present, it can resolve the dependency at build-time for optimization (Dead Code Elimination).
            </p>
           {% highlight "json" %}
// myapp.intents.json
{
  "intents": {
    "motion": "immediate",
    "density": "compact",
    "mode": "night"
  }
}
            {% endhighlight %}
            {% highlight "typescript" %}
// Application Injector Setup
injector App {
    provide { intents } to '@web-intents' from './intents';
    // Or
    provide { intents } to '@web-intents' from './intents.json' with { type: 'json' };
    // Or for run-time resolution, actual .json content can be swapped dynamically
    provide { intents } to '@web-intents' from 'https://myapp.com/intents.json' with { type: 'json' };
}
            {% endhighlight %}
            {% highlight "typescript" %}
// Component Injector Setup
injector Component extends import.injector {
    consume { mode, density } of '@web-intents';
    const { withMode } = await import(`./traits/mode.${mode}`);
    const { density } = await import(`./constants/density.${density}`);
    // Provide to default domain
    provide { withMode, density };
}
            {% endhighlight %}            
            {% highlight "typescript" %}
// Component Source
consume { density, withMode };

class MyComponent extends HTMLElement {
    connectedCallback() {
        this.style.padding = density.spacing.md;
    }
}

withMode(Component); // applies mode trait
            {% endhighlight %}
        </section>

<section id="ssr" class="section-card">
    <h3 id="ssr-contract">SSR Contract</h3>
    <p>
        This section defines the server-side rendering contract for <strong>Web Intents</strong>.
        The server MUST read the intent configuration and apply the active profile's settings to the rendered output.
        This ensures that density, motion, mode, and other UX preferences are reflected in the initial HTML
        without waiting for client-side JavaScript.
    </p>

    <h4 id="ssr-server-output">Server Output Requirements</h4>
    <div class="comparison-table-wrapper mt-4">
        <table class="comparison-table">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Feature</th>
                    <th>Server Output HTML</th>
                    <th>Notes</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Intent configuration</strong></td>
                    <td>
<pre style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.8em;"><code>&lt;html data-intent-density="compact"
      data-intent-motion="immediate"
      data-intent-mode="night"&gt;</code></pre>
                    </td>
                    <td>Server MUST read the intent configuration (e.g., <code>intents.json</code>) and emit the active profile as <code>data-intent-*</code> attributes on the root element or relevant scope.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Density-driven styles</strong></td>
                    <td>
<pre style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.8em;"><code>&lt;div style="padding: 4px 8px;"&gt;
  Compact item
&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>
                    </td>
                    <td>Server MUST apply the active density profile's spacing values to rendered components. Build-time intent resolution allows dead-code elimination of unused density implementations.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Motion preference</strong></td>
                    <td><code>&lt;div class="transition-none"&gt;</code> or appropriate motion class</td>
                    <td>Server MUST apply the motion intent to CSS classes or inline styles. The <code>immediate</code> profile suppresses transition/animation classes.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Context serialization</strong></td>
                    <td>
<pre style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.8em;"><code>&lt;script type="application/json"
  data-store="intents:active"&gt;
{"density":"compact",
 "motion":"immediate",
 "mode":"night"}
&lt;/script&gt;</code></pre>
                    </td>
                    <td>Server MUST serialize the active intent profile using the <a href="/projects/webstates/#ssr">Web States</a> JSON block format so the client can hydrate without re-reading configuration.</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>

    <h4 id="ssr-hydration-expectations">Client Hydration Expectations</h4>
    <ul class="list-disc ml-6 text-gray-600 text-sm">
        <li><strong>Intent verification:</strong> Client reads the serialized intent profile and verifies it matches the current configuration. If the server output is correct, no DOM mutations are needed.</li>
        <li><strong>Dynamic override:</strong> For runtime intent changes (e.g., user toggling density), the client updates <code>data-intent-*</code> attributes and re-applies affected styles. This is a client-only operation.</li>
        <li><strong>Trait loading:</strong> Intent-specific trait implementations (e.g., the physics engine for swipe gestures) are loaded only if the active intent requires them. See <a href="/projects/webcontexts/#ssr">Web Contexts SSR</a> for context resolution.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4 id="ssr-progressive-baseline">Progressive Enhancement Baseline</h4>
    <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">
        With zero JavaScript: all intent-driven styles (density, motion, mode) are applied via HTML attributes and inline styles.
        The <code>data-intent-*</code> attributes can be used as CSS selectors for theme-level styling
        (e.g., <code>[data-intent-mode="night"] { ... }</code>).
        Components render at the server-determined density and mode.
        No dynamic intent switching — the profile is frozen at its server-rendered values.
    </p>

    <h4 id="ssr-client-only">Client-Only Features</h4>
    <ul class="list-disc ml-6 text-gray-600 text-sm">
        <li><strong>Dynamic intent switching:</strong> Changing density, motion, or mode at runtime</li>
        <li><strong>Trait loading:</strong> Lazy-loading intent-specific implementations via <a href="/projects/webtraits/">Web Traits</a></li>
        <li><strong>User preference detection:</strong> Reading <code>prefers-reduced-motion</code>, <code>prefers-color-scheme</code>, and other media queries to auto-configure intents</li>
        <li><strong>Intent composition:</strong> Merging multiple intent profiles from different injector scopes</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(251, 191, 36, 0.1); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #f59e0b; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
        <h4 id="ssr-implementor-note" style="margin-top: 0; color: #d97706; font-size: 1rem;">Implementor Note</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
            This contract defines compliance requirements. The build system or server framework
            is responsible for reading intent configuration, applying the active profile to rendered output,
            and serializing the profile for client hydration.
            Web Intents does not ship an SSR runtime — it ships this specification.
            See also: <a href="/projects/webcontexts/#ssr">Web Contexts SSR Contract</a> for context-based intent resolution.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>